# Library docs — Context7 first

When a task involves a **library, framework, SDK, API, CLI tool, or cloud service**
(even well-known ones like Next.js, React, Tailwind, Three.js, Stripe, Firebase),
prefer the **Context7 MCP** over recalling APIs from memory. Training data may be
stale; Context7 returns current, version-accurate documentation.

## When to use Context7

- API signatures, config options, and setup steps
- Version migration / breaking-change questions
- Library-specific debugging
- CLI usage and flags

## When NOT to use it

- Refactoring or writing app logic from scratch
- Debugging your own business logic
- General programming concepts

## How

1. Resolve the library id, then fetch focused docs for the specific topic.
2. Cite the version/section you relied on when it affects the answer.
3. If Context7 is unavailable, say so and fall back to web docs — do not silently guess an API.

> Rule of thumb: if you are about to write a specific library API call from memory and you are not 100% sure of the current signature, check Context7 first.
